column49: this redesign is disappointing.  Not being able to enter my own due dates, and the smaller number of available titles coupled with the much more expensive prices has kept me from sending this info to families sooner this year.  Many of my student's families have very tight budgets, and historically Scholastic has enabled them to order quality books at very reasonable prices.  Now prices are comparable to Barnes and Noble, but with lesser quality book construction and many fewer titles.  The dollar books and reasonably priced value packs enable me to use points for birthday books as well as holiday gifts for my 50+ preschool students.  This year I won't be able to do both.  I can't afford to pay cash for 50 books at these prices.  I'm afraid class participation in orders will be much lower this year.

column49: I am a parent to a Kindergarten student, visiting the Scholastic website for the first time. I was very excited to learn that my daughter would have the opportunity to buy books through Scholastic, continuing a longstanding family tradition. I fondly recall picking up my copies of all the Babysitters' Club books, all the Goosebump books, and so many more during the Scholastic Book Fairs of my own childhood. I was very disappointed to hear today that Scholastic is choosing to segregate diverse titles. I know the justification from the press release was akin to "Well what do you expect us to do? Some states won't allow us to sell certain books." As a parent, active PTO member, and investor, I am disappointed when your response could just as easily have been "Since some states won't allow us to sell certain books, we won't sell books in those states." I came here today to try to get a full list of the "Share Every Story, Celebrate Every Voice" books so I could go patronize my neighborhood

column49: I have just entered my 20th year of teaching and have always been a HUGE fan of Scholastic Book Clubs. However, I must say that my opinion has changed this year. The prices are extremely high. Also,  I'm not sure why you went back to prices ending in .99 cents. Whole dollar amounts were much easier for my first graders to understand and save up their own money to buy books. Also, as a teacher, I purchase books for my entire class multiple times a year but won't be able to do that this year because the prices are just too high to buy 30 copies of something.  There also seem to be a lot more "toys" in the magazines this year, rather than books. We need our kids to be reading! They are already getting enough play time and I don't think the toys provide any educational value. Lastly, while I know that most people have internet access these days, the fact that parents are no longer able to send a check to the teacher and have the teacher order for them is just not equitable. I work at a tit

column49: The changes made to Scholastic Book Clubs this year make it difficult for my families to have equal access to books.    First of all, the books seem more expensive than they have in the past. The prices are similar to what they would pay in the store and more than the prices at the used book store in our community.    Second, the removal of the order form from the flyer makes it difficult for many of my families to order. Some families don't have access to a computer for online ordering, while others are new to the country and do not have credit cards for online payment.     Thank you for your interest in making the experience better for teachers and the communities they serve.

column49: The changes to Scholastic for this school year are making more work for teachers who already have A LOT on their plates.  I have requested to opt out of the automatic submission of my class orders to which I was told it was not an option to do so.  So, what I take from that is that my class order was auto-submitted, leaving my teacher order in the cart, which I now have to pay shipping if I wish to submit it?  How is this encouraging teachers to use Scholastic?  I don't make a lot of money, teaching in a private school, however I wish to bring books to my families, while also earning the bonus points to essentially get "free" books for my classroom.  If I'm being given no choice but to pay for my shipping unless I remember to submit my order manually in a very specific timeframe, how is that saving me money and why would I continue to use it.  Please, make this right and show your gratitude to teachers who basically help Scholastic to make their money by recommending you to our familie

column49: Please reconsider your policy and promote all books. All children deserve to be uplifted and seen in literature. All stories have a place in homes, schools, libraries, and hands.  Highlight all stories! I urge you to stand with Amanda Gorman and treat all stories with the same value and attention. Our children deserve to know history and make up their own minds about life. Stop censoring voices and content. Use your company to support diversity.  I just started using Scholastic in my classroom after 14 years of being out of the classroom and my students are thrilled to get books! I’d like to continue to offer them your site, as your brand has always brought joy.  Thank you for considering and I hope you rethink your company culture and priorities. Use your platform to promote love.  Thank you,  Donna Paxon

column49: I have been ordering from Scholastic for over 20 years.  Your new ordering system is causing teachers much stress.  No longer having the order form on the back for students to fill out makes it extremely difficult for teachers to receive student orders.  The families in some communities do not possess the resources to place online orders on their own so they send in whatever cash they can with their children to purchase books.  I am also no longer able to  quickly enter a students name and what item numbers they have ordered.  This is making ordering an extremely daunting task.  Please consider allowing teachers to enter student names and item numbers for ease of sorting when orders arrive and please go back to having the order forms on the back of the form.  Thank you.

column49: I do not like/agree with the new way the Scholastic Book Club operates. In the past I usually have class orders near $100 per month. It is confusing to some parents and teachers and some parents simply can't order books online due to not having Internet access or devices. I do not like that there are only certain dates that orders need to be submitted by as well. Also, in previous years, my students loved to look at the numerous flyers and were excited to see what they would like to order. Now they get one small flyer to look at. As of now, if the ordering policy doesn't change, I don't think I will be participating in the Scholastic Book Club much longer.
